# msaa_flatland.tas — MSAA regression test on a flat world.
#
# Purpose: destroy a nearby block and pan the camera to an off-axis angle so
# silhouette diagonals are exposed. Frame diffs between --msaa=none and
# --msaa=4 should produce many ±1 LSB pixel differences (the MSAA signature).
#
# Usage (from utils/swindowzig):
#   zig build native -Dexample=voxel
#   ./zig-out/bin/voxel --world=flatland --msaa=none \
#     --tas examples/voxel/tests/msaa_flatland.tas \
#     --dump-frame=/tmp/flat_none.ppm
#   ./zig-out/bin/voxel --world=flatland --msaa=4 \
#     --tas examples/voxel/tests/msaa_flatland.tas \
#     --dump-frame=/tmp/flat_msaa4.ppm
#   python3 diff-ppm.py /tmp/flat_none.ppm /tmp/flat_msaa4.ppm
#
# Tick numbering is relative to the first post-loading tick (the replayer is
# gated during world load), so tick 1 is always the first frame of gameplay.

# --- Capture mouse ---
1 mouse_down left
2 mouse_up left

# --- Look down so the flat grass surface is in view ---
3 mouse_move 0 180

# --- Destroy the block at the crosshair (digs a 1x1 hole in flat terrain) ---
5 mouse_down left
6 mouse_up left

# --- Pan rightward to expose the diagonal edges of the hole at an angle ---
# 8 ticks of rightward pan @ 4px/tick = 32px total.
8 mouse_move 4 0
9 mouse_move 4 0
10 mouse_move 4 0
11 mouse_move 4 0
12 mouse_move 4 0
13 mouse_move 4 0
14 mouse_move 4 0
15 mouse_move 4 0

# --- Tilt up slightly so the horizon is in frame (more diagonal silhouettes) ---
16 mouse_move 0 -40

# Hold steady a few ticks so the --dump-frame capture lands on a stable view.
20 mouse_move 0 0
